The paper deals with the design of storage-efficient algorithms for emulating atomic shared memory over an asynchronous, distributed message-passing network. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of erasure-coding techniques, which are commonly used in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also discusses the storage size and communication rounds required for the algorithms, which are relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper's focus on liveness and termination properties suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the use of a distributed message-passing network suggests that the paper may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
